<div class="bibEntry"><p class="bib">158. Pope, Arthur. The Language of Drawing and Painting. 1949 Reprint.New York: Russell and Russell, 1967. 200 pp. Appendix, B/W illus., color illus. </p><p class="annot">Inspired by the color scales and color triangles developed by histeacher, Denman Ross, here Arthur Pope discusses his own color theories and explains the three dimensional cylinder he developed to express the relationships of the traditional 12 hue circle. His earlier writings on modes of drawing and painting, and on color are summarized in this publication with many illustrations of historic drawings and paintings. Howard T. Fisher puts the Popeâ€™s work in perspective in his Color in Art (1974). </p></div>
